post_text:
As we prepare for the Class of 2020's virtual graduation ceremony I would like to thank the staff of Markham Place for all of their hard work and dedication to the students. I also, want to thank the students for their grit and determination in facing the challenges of remote learning. Also, the parents and community for supporting the staff and students through all that this year has thrown at them.

Thank you to the PTO for all your help with the end of the year "celebrations" for the Class of 2020. From gifts, parade route planning and honks of happiness, to the most important...the amazing slide show at the conclusion of the graduation ceremony.

To the students and families of the Class of 2020 you have left your mark in the history of Markham Place and helped to forward our story and traditions in ways we didn't know were going to be thrust upon us. You did it with class, hard work, and true Warrior Spirit. You will be missed. Best of luck in high school.

Mr. Platt

#ALONETOGETHER #CLASSOF2020 #WARRIORS

post_text:
From the LS Police Dept.:The long-needed repairs to Markham Place have begun. The process began today, June 8th, and will continue for the next 2 to 3 weeks. The first phase of this restoration is repairs to the curbs and sidewalks. When that work is complete the contractor will move to complete other concrete work within the Borough. Milling and paving will be completed sometime either in the last week of June or early July.

The construction on Markham will be a moving work zone, as the contractor finishes one area they will move to another section of the road. This means that the are of Markham that was closed off one day may not be the same area closed off the next. There will be NO through traffic on Markham. Residents in the area closed on any given day will only have access through the area the police officer is stationed. Please be aware of where the officer is that day. Access to Valley Bank will be allowed during this project, but will be limited during paving.

post_text: On Wednesday, May 27th from 7:00- 7:30, we invite all orchestra, chorus and band students to go out on their front yards and porches to perform music from the Spring Concert or method books! We hope to fill the neighborhoods of Little Silver with amazing music! Parents are welcome to send a 15-20 second MP4 formatted video clip or picture of your child’s performance to jbrush@littlesilverschools.org by May 29th. A short movie of the concert will be shared with the community. Thank you for your support of music education and the arts at this time!
text: On Wednesday, May 27th from 7:00- 7:30, we invite all orchestra, chorus and band students to go out on their front yards and porches to perform music from the Spring Concert or method books! The results that you have been waiting for Field Day Week 1 standings. This week's challenge is If The Shoe Fits. Details on the PE Google Classroom.

CALLING ALL ARTIST!
Do you have a piece of artwork that you have created while we have been on remote learning? Do you want to create something new just for this show? Have you tried to make something from nature? Have you made something from the things you have recycled? You are only limited by your imagination! Let’s see how creative you can be!

When you are ready to submit your artwork take a picture of it as close as you can and make sure it's in a well-lit area. PLEASE SEND ALL PHOTOGRAPHS OF ARTWORK TO prartshow2020@littlesilverschools.org

When you email your entry, please put your name and grade level in the email message so that we are able to organize the show by grade level. The submission deadline is Thursday, May 28th Here is the link for directions
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1zM_dnNy1OmHhAHClZtV8ZCrS7mApSPnP/view?usp=sharing

post_text:
Normally, we begin collecting back our library books at the end of May. Despite all that is different, this year is no exception. An inventory of our collection allows us to replace and refresh our books where needed and ensures our students will have the materials they need for the new year.

That’s why during the weeks of May 18th and 25th
Point Road’s front vestibule will be open from 9am - 2pm.
Please drop off your books in one of the three available bins, white bins on the right side of the vestibule.

Any books that remain checked out after June 1st
will receive an email notice and may be subject to a potential fine.

Thank you for your help!
Karen Seligman
Media Assistant

The Annual Meeting of the Little Silver PTO has been postponed from the originally scheduled time of May 14, 2020 at 7pm. The meeting will be held on June 11, 2020 at 7pm. Due to the restrictions on in person meetings, the meeting will be conducted via Zoom. 2020-21 Officers and Board will be elected at the meeting, all PTO members are invited to attend. Full agenda will be provided in advance of the meeting.

Time: June 11, 2020 07:00 PM Eastern Time (US and Canada)



Zoom Meeting Details will be provided in advance of the meeting.

The First Five Minutes is a new project for the month of May. Throughout the month, Mrs. Seligman is going to introduce you to chapter books that are a bit overlooked in the library. There's no assignment except to listen as she reads the first five minutes of a book. Just sit back, relax, and see if the story is one you want to continue reading on your own. She is selecting books that are most appropriate for older readers, but all of these also make great family read-alouds. If you like the first five minutes, leave a response video and let her know what you liked best and if you plan to read the whole book! We hope you find something new to read and love!

post_text: Did you know that on this date in 1872 the first Arbor Day was celebrated in Nebraska City, Nebraska? It's estimated that nearly one million trees were planted on this day. Little Silver has celebrated Arbor Day since 1964 and most years the kindergarten students present a special program to help us remember the importance of Arbor Day. Since 1979 each kindergarten student received a tree seedling to plant at home. Help us celebrate this year by planting an acorn in your yard.

post_text:
Is anyone else missing their Crossing Guards???? We know many of you have built special relationships with the people that keep our children safe on the way to and from school! If you want to write a note or send a card to that special crossing guard, now is the time! There is a collection box in the vestibule of police headquarters (entrance on the side of the building by Wells Fargo.) Just drop your note in the box, where they will be collected, sorted, and distributed to the correct recipient! See the list of names and locations for you to use!
Let's show our crossing guards how much they mean to us!

post_text: We have received some exciting news from the Borough of Little Silver!! The Easter Bunny will be traveling through town to wish everyone well! Look for our visitor between 1 and 3 p.m. on Saturday, April 11. Please observe social distancing, wave to our good friend from your own property only, and do not approach the Easter Bunny, who wants everyone to stay well! We wish everyone of all faiths the joys of the season, even as we continue to follow the governor's orders, and we ask everyone to keep in your thoughts and prayers those who have been directly affected by the virus. Be well, stay safe, stay home, and steel your resolve as we approach better days. Hippity Hoppity!

Our Child Study Team will be hosting conversations about important topics that can support our students at home!

Youtube available Mondays at 11am

If you have questions for the panelists please email swhite@littlesilverschools.org subject "PODCAST ITEM"

post_text:
The first day of spring falls on Thursday, March 19th at 11:50pm EDT, which is earlier than it's been in over a century The last time spring arrived this early was in 1896, 124 years ago.
Did you know? Congress authorized Daylight Savings Time on March 19, 1918.
